ars in her grandmother's home, advances through the professoriate and senior administration, and addresses her hopes and fears for her own children. Drawing inspiration from the African American storytelling traditions she has spent decades studying and teaching, Lee approaches issues of race, gender, social justice, academic labor, and leadership with a voice that is clear, intimate, and humorous. As she writes in the introduction, "Sisterlocking Discoarse is about braiding and breathing and believing that a Black woman's journey through the academy is important." Lee's journey will appeal to students, faculty, and administrators across fields and institutions who are committed to making higher education more inclusive, while speaking to the experiences of professional women of color more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American women college teachersvBiography. 0aAfrican American women in higher education. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aEducation : Educational Administration. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Educators.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848586740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438485867423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438485867/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles